{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8887c566-0f15-4889-bda0-9c6e26176284","content":"No repo-specific docs on this topic. Here's the general guidance:\n\nOn macOS, when `createdump` isn't available (common with NativeAOT since it's not bundled), you can recover crash dumps via the OS:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/core.%P\n   ```\n\n2. **Re-run the app** to reproduce the crash. macOS will write a core file to the configured path.\n\n3. **Check `/cores/`** — macOS may also write dumps to `/cores/core.<pid>` (requires SIP configuration on newer versions).\n\n4. **Use the Console app** or check `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` for `.crash` log files generated automatically by `ReportCrash`.\n\n5. **Analyze** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you can attach `lldb` proactively:\n   ```bash\n   lldb /path/to/your/app\n   run\n   # after crash, use `bt` for backtrace\n   ```\n\nThe `.crash` files in `DiagnosticReports` are often the easiest starting point — they're generated automatically and contain stack traces without any prior configuration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4941d7b2-f4d2-4d79-a4e2-0d03e18e27f6","outputTokens":343},"id":"fba2455f-c2c7-4674-8a38-9bafcb4e07bb","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:02:10.947Z","parentId":"83886bd2-d408-42ee-b3bb-a7c33c94788c"}
